SIMPLE: antagonist
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: antagonist
<hw>an*tag"o*nist</hw> <pr>(⟦acr⟧n*t⟦acr⟧g"⟦osl⟧*n⟦icr⟧st)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>antagonista</ets>, Gr.
<grk>'antagwnisth`s</grk>; <grk>'anti`</grk> against +
<grk>'agwnisth`s</grk> combatant, champion, fr.
<grk>'agwni`zesqai</grk>: cf. F. <ets>antagoniste</ets>. See
<er>Antagonism</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who contends with
another, especially in combat; an adversary; an opponent.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Antagonist</qex> of Heaven's Almighty King.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Our <qex>antagonists</qex> in these controversies.</q>
<rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>A muscle which acts in opposition
to another; <as>as a <i>flexor</i>, which bends a part, is the
<ex>antagonist</ex> of an <i>extensor</i>, which extends it</as>.</def>
<ver>AS</ver>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A substance which opposes the
actions of another substance in the body, especially a drgu that
counteracts the effects of another drug.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> + <source>AS</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Adversary; enemy; opponent; foe; competitor. See
<er>Adversary</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Antagonist</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Antagonist
<hw>An*tag"o*nist</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Antagonistic; opposing;
counteracting; <as>as, <ex>antagonist</ex> schools of
philosophy</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Antagonistic</ent>⟦br⟧
